The SARIMA model specification is {ARIMA (1,1,1) (1,1,1)12}
(1−ϕ1B)(1−Φ1B12)(1−B)(1−B12)yt=(1+θ1B)(1+β1B12)et
where (1−ϕ1B) = non-seasonal AR(1), (1−Φ1B12) = seasonal AR(1), (1 –B) = non-seasonal difference, (1 –B12) = seasonal difference, yt = forecasted value, (1+θ1B) = non-seasonal MA(1), (1+β1B12) = seasonal MA(1), et = error term.

To detect the serial correlation of the univariate SARIMA models, the Ljung-Box Q statistic was used, and the Shapiro-Wilk test and Kolmogorov-Smirnov test were used to detect the normality of residuals. The Ljung-Box Q statistic was calculated using the following equation:
Q(m)=n(n+2)∑j=1mrj2n−j;
where Q(m) = Ljung-Box Q statistic, m = time lag, rj = accumulated sample autocorrelation, n = length of the time series.

The test statistic (W) of the Shapiro-Wilk test was calculated as follows:
W=(∑i=1naix(i))2∑i=1n(xi−x¯)2;
where x(i) = ith order statistics, ai = coefficient calculated by the covariance matrix, x¯ = sample mean.

The test statistic (Dn) of the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test was calculated as follows:
Dn=supx|Fn(x)−F(x)|;
where supx = supremum of the set of distances and F = distribution function.
